## Plan & Task Numbering Convention

### Workflow Gates (MUST follow)

**BEFORE creating a plan doc** (`docs/implementation/*_PLAN.md`):
1. `gh issue create -R {owner}/{repo} --label plan --title "{title}"` → get `P#N`
2. Put `plan_id: P#N` in the plan doc frontmatter
3. Run `/task-evaluate` on the plan before it is considered ready

**BEFORE starting implementation of a plan phase or standalone task**:
1. `gh issue create -R {owner}/{repo} --label task --title "{title}"` → get `T#N`
2. Run `/task-execute` for the implementation — do NOT implement directly without the harness
3. Reference `T#N` in commit messages: `feat(T#N): description`

**BEFORE committing**:
- Verify the commit message references a `T#N` or `P#N` (except trivial fixes)

### Harness Skills (MUST use)

- `/task-evaluate`: ANY plan, spec, or design doc before implementation begins.
- `/task-execute`: ANY non-trivial implementation work (code, fixtures, config).

**When to skip**: only truly trivial operations — single-line typo fixes, commit/push, file reads, or answering questions. If in doubt, use the harness.

### Numbering Source

GitHub Issues per repo. Plans = `P#N` (label `plan`); tasks = `T#N` (label `task`). Cross-repo ref `{repo}#N`; in-repo `#N`. Offline fallback: repo-local sequential numbers, resolved on merge.

### Rules

- Do NOT retroactively renumber existing plans/tasks — apply to new work only.
- Plan and task numbers are per-repo (not globally unique).
- Use GitHub Issue labels (`plan`, `task`) to distinguish P# from T#.
